@smajida , you really don't have enough RAM to run this example. As I see on your images, you have only 2.8 GB available. 23 seconds ago there were a peak of memory usage (90%) - I think the example was running this time and it was not able to allocate required amount of memory

[The reason are this lines of code inside example](https://github.com/davisking/dlib/blob/master/examples/dnn_mmod_face_detection_ex.cpp#L91-L92):

```C++
        while(img.size() < 1800*1800)
            pyramid_up(img);
```

I recommend you to comment this lines and try to recompile and run example

@supervacuus I never intended to hijack this thread :-) I know you were the person who wrote the pybind11 stuff and that's why I mentioned you, so that you could eyeball the new stuff better. I appreciate your contributions!

@davisking I did some further research and here is what I found:
How to bind and return `matrix<rgb_pixel>` directly:
```
#include <pybind11/numpy.h>
matrix<rgb_pixel> get_face_chip (
    py::object img,
    const full_object_detection& face,
    size_t size = 150,
    float padding = 0.25
)
{
    if (!is_rgb_python_image(img))
        throw dlib::error("Unsupported image type, must be RGB image.");

    matrix<rgb_pixel> chip;
    extract_image_chip(numpy_rgb_image(img), get_face_chip_details(face, size, padding), chip);
    return chip;
}
```
and
```
    typedef matrix<rgb_pixel> type;
    py::class_<type>(m, "image", py::buffer_protocol())
   .def_buffer([](type &m) -> py::buffer_info {
        return py::buffer_info(
            image_data(m),                                      /* Pointer to buffer */
            sizeof(npy_uint8),                                  /* Size of one scalar */
            py::format_descriptor<npy_uint8>::format(),         /* Python struct-style format descriptor */
            3,                                                  /* Number of dimensions */
            { num_rows(m), num_columns(m), 3UL },               /* Buffer dimensions */
            { sizeof(npy_uint8) * num_columns(m) * 3,           /* Strides (in bytes) for each index */
              sizeof(npy_uint8) * 3,
              sizeof(npy_uint8) }
        );
    });
```

This works, and in Python, you would show the image as follows:
```
# Get the aligned face image
dlib_image = dlib.get_face_chip(img, face, size=320)
count = sys.getrefcount(dlib_image)
assert count == 2, "Memory leak detected in get_face_chip"
image = np.array(dlib_image, copy=False) # This step is necessary as dlib_image is of type dlib.image
count = sys.getrefcount(dlib_image)
assert count == 3, "Unexpected ref count for dlib image"
count = sys.getrefcount(image)
assert count == 2, "Unexpected ref count for numpy array"
window = dlib.image_window()
window.set_image(image)
window.wait_until_closed()
```

We **have** to initialize the array with `np.array(dlib.get_face_chip(img, face, size=320), copy=False)` which is non-ideal. So I prefer @supervacuus approach, unless we can find something else.

One more thing. Since, we are returning a numpy array, we know the dimensions will be H x W x 3. I did not get why we need to use `sizeof(rgb_pixel)`. Shouldn't the code be:
```
pybind11::array_t<uint8_t> create_array_from_rgb_image(const matrix<rgb_pixel> &rgb_image)
{
    const size_t dtype_size = sizeof(uint8_t);
    const auto rows = static_cast<const size_t>(num_rows(rgb_image));
    const auto cols = static_cast<const size_t>(num_columns(rgb_image));
    const size_t channels = 3;
    const size_t image_size = dtype_size * rows * cols * channels;

    auto arr = new uint8_t[image_size];
    memcpy(arr, image_data(rgb_image), image_size);

    return pybind11::array_t<uint8_t>(
        {rows, cols, channels},                                                     // shape
        {dtype_size * cols * channels, dtype_size * channels, dtype_size},          // strides
        arr,                                                                        // pointer
        pybind11::capsule{
            arr, [](void *arr_p) {
                delete[] reinterpret_cast<uint8_t *>(arr_p);
            }
        }
    );
}
```

With this, the Python code becomes dead simple:
```
# Get the aligned face image
image = dlib.get_face_chip(img, face, size=320)
count = sys.getrefcount(image)
assert count == 2, "Memory leak detected in get_face_chip"
window = dlib.image_window()
window.set_image(image)
window.wait_until_closed()
```

