This looks suspect:
```C++
    py::class_<BarI, std::unique_ptr<BarI>> bar( m, "BarI" );
    foo.def( "bla", &BarI::bla );
```
`bla` is defined as a bound method on `Foo`, but then bound to a function of `BarI`.  Thus when pybind11 tries to dispatch `foo.bla()` it will see that `bla` has one entry with first argument type `BarI`, but you gave it a first argument of type `Foo`, so it won't match.

In my slapd setup I have only timestamps and timestamps with millisecond when returns from pwdFailureTime.

This is an example code I use to parse these.

````
import time
from datetime import datetime
from django.utils import timezone

from django.conf import settings

LDAP_DATETIME_FORMAT = '%Y%m%d%H%M%SZ'
LDAP_DATETIME_MILLISECONDS_FORMAT = '%Y%m%d%H%M%S.%fZ'

def parse_time(timestr, tformat):
    time_struct = time.strptime(timestr, tformat)
    timestamp = time.mktime(time_struct)
    return timezone.get_current_timezone().localize(timezone.datetime.fromtimestamp(timestamp))

def parse_generalized_time(timestr):
    return parse_time(timestr, settings.LDAP_DATETIME_FORMAT)

def parse_pwdfailure_time(timestr):
    return parse_time(timestr, settings.LDAP_DATETIME_MILLISECONDS_FORMAT)
````

Would you like to introduce a specialized field like SlapdDateTimeField?
We could introduce also dateutils for automagic datetime parse but I wouldn't carry too much things on Field Classes. I think that it would be better to know which format returns from a LDAP attribute and use the correct FieldType in model definition.

